 "publication": {
  "pmid": "25471691",
  "doi": "10.1002/eji.201445114",
  "title": "Structural basis for ineffective T-cell responses to MHC anchor residue-improved \"heteroclitic\" peptides.",
  "journal": "European journal of immunology",
  "year": 2015,
  "authors": "Madura F, Rizkallah PJ, Holland CJ, Fuller A, Bulek A, Godkin AJ, Schauenburg AJ, Cole DK, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined the TCR recognition of wild-type and engineered variants of the MART-1/Melan-A peptide (EAAGIGILTV and its leucine-2 heteroclitic variant ELAGIGILTV) bound to HLA-A*0201 using crystal structures of a TCR\u2013pMHC complex. The key finding was that the suboptimal MHC anchor residue in the natural peptide allows the TCR to mechanically \"pull\" the peptide away from the binding groove, creating additional TCR contact points with both peptide and MHC that are absent in the higher-affinity heteroclitic variant. This structural mechanism explains a critical problem in cancer immunotherapy: T cells primed with the heteroclitic peptide fail to efficiently recognize the natural tumor-expressed antigen, potentially accounting for clinical trial failures. The work demonstrates that while heteroclitic peptides improve MHC binding and elicit stronger initial immune responses, they may paradoxically reduce cross-reactivity to the native epitope by inducing a conformational state that does not match the TCR-engaged geometry of the wild-type peptide. These findings highlight the extreme conformational sensitivity of TCR recognition and the complex trade-offs between enhancing MHC stability and maintaining tumor-relevant antigen recognition in peptide-based cancer vaccines.",
